social_posts.post_text: Sorry if that last post made my kid look unbelievably good at coloring, the stuff that was inside the lines was me (and so are the drawings) but here’s some of our more collaborative work. She loves to make it look like rabbits have blood coming out of every orifice, which is mildly concerning.

Wow that Lensa app sure is something, AI art is truly the future. Too long have human artists been gouging us with their expensive beach boardwalk caricatures in order to make a living. Those greedy starving artists can go paint themselves some golden parachutes, soulless procedurally generated by data-harvesting algorithms is the future!

The cool thing about posing stuffed animals instead of action figures is they all kind of stick together and also if they fall off the shelf they don’t explode into a million pieces unless they’re some sort of novelty prank plushies. Anyway tag yourself. NOTE: this isn’t all of them so if you gave my kid a stuffed animal and you’re like “wtf” trying to find it, I assure you: it’s probably behind the couch.

Parenthood is going just fine. Anyway, huge thanks to @dlohridah for helping connect me with a dude who had this Sentinel and was down to trade it for the equally large Galactus that I pre-ordered even though I don’t really like Galactus. I did maybe the most bizarre action figure drug deal with an internet stranger that was straight out of Jingle All The Way. Anyway I realized that the Sentinels were basically my first exposure to giant robots. There’s something hilarious about a twenty foot tall bigot robot that looks like a crash test dummy crossed with a Barbie dream house. In other news, my actual child is alive and well and we all had a lovely Christmas break and I took a lot of pictures but I only felt like sharing this one of the big X-Men doll making lewd gestures. Happy new year, everybody!

Happy friggin Wednesday hope everyone’s having a nice healthy January, balancing out the bleakest month of the year by denying yourself all of life’s best treats and vices. I’ll start eating vegetables once the Christmas cookies are gone.

In a shocking turn of events, my kid has shown interest in toys and miniatures and figurines and other fun colorful trinkets. Also there’s a killer hobby shop hidden past the plumbing section in the Ace Hardware on Milvia St. in downtown Berkeley.
My dog is still alive and well despite me not posting photos all the time or not feeding him whenever he barks and spins in a circle and stares at me.
Sure, it’s the 8th most expensive city in the world but can you put a price tag on culture?

People have expressed interest in this in the past, so I figured I’d put the offer on the table. Shoot me a DM and we can take it from there, I guess? I’ll respond in as timely a fashion as possible. Happy to answer any questions in the comments. The vet told us we need to switch Peppers to organic mayonnaise and he eats about a quart so the bills are piling up and it was either this or selling foot pics on one of those erotic nudity websites for perverts.
Pre-dawn portrait session brought to you in part by drinking cold brew concentrate straight
Found the mix CD that made my wife fall in love with me

Plate me like one of your French girls.

(We had a Titanic-themed costume party for reasons I don’t feel like typing out or fully understand myself)
Here’s a commission I did last week! Acrylic on canvas. I cropped it because I’m obsessive about not breaking my streak of square images on this dumb app.

Another commission. Acrylic and paint marker on canvas. Please do not fixate on the light logic or perspective of the dodecahedron, they are extremely complicated shapes. Some have upwards of 20 sides and easily a dozen vertices.
Dawn of the Dad
Happy birthday to my number one dude @awwpeppers who turned 8 today. This special guy is getting an extra cup of fancy mayonnaise in his bowl today for being so great.

My sweet funny little kid turned two this week and it’s mind-boggling how fast that happened. All the cliche dad stuff is embarrassingly true and I love her more every day, but more importantly I just think she’s a cool person. I usually avoid posting photos of her face on social media, so here are a few where she’s partially obscured but still obviously very cute.
Here’s a lil goblin I made for a commission. Body is polymer clay and the hat is metal scraps. Shoot me a DM if you want me to make some art or whatever.
Somebody commissioned a chicken. A commicken? No. Get out of here with that.
Metal Gear Rex Vs. Metal Gear Ray

We had a bunch of these crappy little paint sets left over from a little paint-by-numbers party we threw (like, a literal one) so I knocked out this happy rabbit housing a couple succulent corn dogs. Also, @tavour mailed me a box of exotic beers to check out, so I cracked this raspberry sour ale from @martinhousebrewing which is excellent. The beer can design may have had a slight influence on the subject matter of my painting, but it’s not exactly out of character for me to draw animals in Hawaiian shirt standing around looking stupid. Anyway, if you’d like a box of exotic beer in the mail, check out @tavour and use the coupon code “peppers” in the app you spend $25 and you’ll get $10 credit towards your next purchase. Also, I bought these @cadburyusa mini eggs with my own damn money and I don’t have any coupon codes, but you should grab some of those the next time you’re in the seasonal candy aisle because they’re the best. Actually, I lied, I bought the bag, but the plastic egg full of them was from my wife’s boss’s wife. These photos would look better with some of that green plastic Easter hay, but that stuff has gotta be a distant relative of asbestos insulation. Anyway, hoppy Friday everybody.

I’m terrible at consistently doing literally anything productive, so let’s see if I can keep this up. The theme for day 1 of #inktober is “DREAM” which is an idiotically vague and open-ended prompt, so here’s a picture of me napping on the couch. Yesterday my wife made fun of me for saying the best way to nap is to fold your arms like a mummy and stare cross-eyed at the inside of your own forehead with your eyes closed, but I’ve had great success with this method. #inktober2023
One of my favorite things to do is eat a big sausage at the Alameda flea market while wearing a Judas Priest shirt so here’s a picture of doing that exact activity

Here’s a nice little Rom The Vacuous Spider from the hit video game Bloodborne, a horrible cosmic spider that lives in a lake surrounded by other equally horrible but less cosmic spiders and who is a real pain in the ass to fight but is pretty cool otherwise. I’m severely arachnophobic but for whatever reason these guys didn’t set me off. That said I do periodically wake up in the dead of night and remember that Goliath bird-eating spiders are real and then I can’t sleep anymore. Oh yeah, “SPIDERS” was the prompt for day 2 of #inktober. Happy #inktober2023

Okay here’s #inktober day 3, today’s prompt is “PATH” which I wasn’t wild about and I wasn’t wild about this drawing initially but then I started getting all silly with the foliage and it worked better. I’m trying to get out of my comfort zone, which is drawing weird ugly dudes from the shoulders up, holding something with one hand against a blank backdrop. Instead, here’s a wide shot of a weird ugly dude holding onto a bicycle with both hands with a forest path in the background. #inktober2023

The challenge for #inktober day 3 is “DODGE” so here’s a Dodge Challenger having a challenging time getting the proverbial F-word outta Dodge, which I learned today is in Kansas. Meanwhile, Kansas City is in Missouri, Nevada City is in California, and the state bird of Utah is the California Gull. Unbelievable. Anyway. Happy #inktober2023 I’ll be back tomorrow with another cool picture I worked hard on that the instagram algorithm buries in favor of AI-generated 90s school portraits. 🤠

Today’s #inktober word was “MAP.” I love maps, but I don’t like drawing them, and I didn’t know what to do here. In fact, complained about it so much my wife called me a curmudgeon. So, here’s a sketch of a framed print I have in my kitchen of a Ruth Gannett illustration of West Cornwall, CT. Among other things, Ruth illustrated the book “My Father’s Dragon,” and was a Cornwall native. Last year I went back to visit and was blown away to see a print of hers hanging in @thecornwallctlibrary showing the town from the exact opposite perspective, which made the whole universe feel a little bit smaller. And I guess that’s why I like maps in general. They make the scale of everything a little easier to take in, even if they’re boring to draw. #inktober2023

I don’t know what it says that it took almost a week for me to realize that #inktober doesn’t have to be black and white. I have plenty of different colored ink but at this point I feel committed to this particular approach. Today’s word is “golden” and this is a golden retriever stealing a golden brown corn dog from someone at a street fair, probably during golden hour somewhere in the golden state. Anyway I took a picture of this balanced on a watermelon because the lighting was good. Happy #inktober2023 to all who observe.

DRIP. I had a lot of fun with this one, I realized xenomorphs were some of my earliest fan art. I was absolutely terrified of them as a kid. I didn’t see the movies, probably just saw an ad for Alien3 on TV. After that, I’d be scared of the Kenner figures at KB Toys and would hide behind the couch when the commercials came on. I saw the arcade game at a boardwalk and had nightmares about the cabinet art. Real wiener kid. At some point that phobia turned into a fascination, and I started doodling them. I didn’t wind up finally watching the movies until years later, and now I read massive hardcover books about how they got made. You know Giger insisted on using real human bones when he was designing that costume? Weirdly, the skulls showed up from a medical supply company with perfect teeth, which inspired Dan O’Bannon to write the scene in Return of the Living Dead where they talk about third world skeleton farms. Anyway, in #inktober2023 nobody can hear you scream.

I don’t think I’ve ever drawn a horned (horny?) toad before but “TOAD” is the word of the day so here’s one of those little bastards living up to his namesake, ogling a dirty magazine he found in your backyard. I’m sure it’s not yours, some neighbor kids must’ve thrown it over the fence to get you in trouble. #inktober #inktober2023

Today for #inktober we’re doing “BOUNCE” and apologies for going the obvious route with a picture you’ve probably seen dozens of times already today. I was giggling to myself drawing this, imagining a kid on a trampoline going “WATCH THIS” shortly before projectile vomiting, and any onlookers being unsure if that was what he wanted people to see or if he was throwing up for unrelated reasons. Makes you think. #inktober2023
Guess what’s on the counter

Today’s prompt was “FORTUNE.” The saying is, “fortune favors the bold,” but today was very long and I’m tired so here’s “Bib Fortuna savors the bold party blend Chex Mix.” I will not be accepting questions at this time. Good night. #inktober #inktober2023

Day whatever today is of #inktober is “WANDER,” so here’s very quick sketch of a photo I took months ago while wandering around Oakland. Not my favorite prompt, interpretation thereof, or execution, but I did the assignment. Maybe I’ll cheat and touch it up tomorrow after I’ve slept on it. Bobcats are hella cool and I’d like to draw one in the wild, not from a photo. Truck or animal, whichever. #inktober2023

Today’s #inktober prompt is “SPICEY” and it’s certainly a spicy take to spell it that wrong but sure, who’s keeping track. Anyway. Here’s me, a guy whose name is synonymous with “the spiciest something can be” giving the stinkeye to a Bloody Mary that might be TOO spicy. Such a thing does exist: years ago @brianaltano dumped about a tablespoon of Dave’s Insanity Sauce into an otherwise innocent adult breakfast gazpacho and after about two sips I got stomach cramps and immediately had to take a shit. That would have been a great prank if he hadn’t made one for himself that was just as painful. We’ve since reconciled. Anyway, spicy food rules and like they say, “variety is the spice of life,” but also “fear is the mind-killer,” and “the spice must flow,” so don’t be a food baby and eat more stuff with a little kick.

Rise from your grave! “RISE” is today’s #inktober word so here’s some zombies. I used to be OBSESSED with zombies and drew a lot of them. Not sure when exactly that stopped, probably when they went from a low-budget joke to a viable blockbuster genre. With my first paycheck from my first job in high school, I bought a DVD player and copies of Goonies, Office Space, and the original 1978 Dawn of the Dead. I still have the last one in a box of keepsakes somewhere, because it’s that special. That was my favorite zombie movie for a while, but I think Return of the Living Dead has since eclipsed it. ‘Dawn’ is a phenomenal film and a great commentary on capitalism and police brutality, but Return’s soundtrack alone makes it so goddamn rewatchable. If you haven’t seen one or both of these movies, please watch them (they’re too old and janky to be scary) and if you have, you’re probably itching for a rewatch now. Anyway. Go zombies, happy #inktober2023
The local library hung up a doodle that I left behind last time I was there. I’m way more proud of this than I should be.

Write a caption... Yesterday I was very bad and didn’t do my #inktober homework, so I did double to make up for it. Theme was “CASTLE,” so I tried to do a quasi-realistic version of one of my favorite LEGO sets as a kid, Wolfpack Tower. I wasn’t happy with how it turned out so I tried to do the same thing with a Playmobil castle I always wanted but never got, Baron’s Battle Tower. I’m not sure why, but I’ve always been obsessed with this particular design. It hit me a few years back that one of the main things I find appealing about fantasy video games is exploring castles, which hits similar notes to playing with LEGO and Playmobil castles as a kid. There’s a watchtower in Skyrim, specifically that reminds me so much of this one Playmobil set. A lot of hardcore gamer doodz love FromSoft’s games for the the challenge, but I’m there for the exploration and the architecture. That “ah ha!” moment of opening a door that unlocks a shortcut has a certain action featurey sensation that reminds me of playing with little LEGO trap doors and secret entrances, like the two cliff walls of Wolfpack tower that swing open so you can make the ghost guard the treasure chest Anyway. Happy double #inktober2023

Today’s #inktober word is “DAGGER,” which is a fun cool thing to draw, but I was sort of tuckered out from drawing castles so here’s this woodland buffoon who fancies himself a real highwayman. If I was feeling ambitious, I would’ve set up a still life of the surprisingly large knife collection I’ve semi-ironically and accidentally accumulated.  I’ve got like, handmade bowie knives, an antique Indonesian kris, a World War One bayonet, one of those tacticool Navy SEAL tantos from that company with the hilarious YouTube channel where they’re always hacking up sisal rugs and pieces of raw pork with replica scimitars and stuff. If you haven’t seen them, look up “Cold Steel” it’s some of the funniest shit I’ve seen on the internet this decade. Anyway, #inktober2023 continues.

Today’s #inktober thingy is “ANGEL,” so here’s a detail from a Hieronymus Bosch painting of people flying on a fish. As far as I’m concerned, that might be Bosch’s idea of an angel. I don’t love this one, and I tried to do a couple other little Bosch sketches and I hated those even more. His stuff is so nonsensical it’s hard to recreate. I did something stupid to my back/neck last night and spent most of today sprawled out on a heating pad sitting as still as possible and guzzling more ibuprofen than usual, unsurprisingly hunching over a miniature ink drawing while wrangling a misbehaving toddler hasn’t been great evening entertainment. Anyway. #inktober2023

Todays #inktober word is “DEMON,” and I didn’t draw my dog, but I did draw the spoiler-y little homage to the final scene of Hereditary that’s hiding behind him. Hereditary is one of my favorite movies in recent years, probably ever. I’m probably due for a rewatch. Hail King Paimon! Hail #inktober2023

The last few of these I’ve done half-awake right before bed, and here’s one I did half-awake first thing this morning. Today’s #inktober prompt is “SADDLE,” which is fun enough since I like drawing weird dudes riding on weird creatures. I’m not sure when this started, it’s obviously a totally primal archetype, but in a pop-cultural sense. Star Wars has Sandtroopers and Dewbacks, Lord of the Rings has Warg Riders. Heavy Metal has Taarna riding her weird Pterodactyl, which is heavily borrowed from Moebius’ Arzach. Ralph Bakshi’s Wizards has Necron 99. Avatar’s got Na’vi riding all sorts of space animals. The list goes on. The tattoo I have of a cowboy riding a slug dinosaur was loosely based on a scene in The Venture Bros where a cowboy is riding on a T-Rex. I think he has a flamethrower. Anyway, not sure who this guy is or what he’s riding, but like him. #inktober2023

Today’s #inktober is “PLUMP” so here’s little doodle of me in my huskier, more rotund and otherwise plumper teenage years. I’m pretty sure I took this photo with the intention of sending it to potential internet girlfriends, but it was on actual film and I have no idea if I ever figured out how to digitize it. The sign on the door had a drawing of Master Roshi from Dragon Ball Z that said “Aloha, Welcome To Max’s Room” but I think maybe 4 or 5 people other than my mom ever went in that room while I lived there. I’ve been on kind of a Dragon Ball kick lately, which has me thinking back to my awkward teenage years. Anyway, back then I used to draw a lot of self-portraits, trying to make myself look as cool as possible, so I guess here’s the opposite.  I still have that Nosferatu figure on the top shelf, wish I’d held onto the Dexter’s Lab mech below it. #inktober2023

Unsurprisingly, social obligations, yard work and long overdue housekeeping have gotten me behind on #inktober. Here’s Friday’s prompt “FROST,” a nice chilly R.J. MacReady from John Carpenter’s The Thing. Or maybe it’s The Thing. or maybe the dog is The Thing, because here’s the thing: anything can be The Thing. I always loved MacReady’s inexplicably large Antarctic cowboy hat, and the part where he pours Scotch into the chess computer is probably the closest any film has come to capturing my mental state for most of 2020. Borderline perfect film, my only lament is that Carpenter didn’t score it. Morricone is no slouch, I’m just a sucker for John’s synthy beats. Maybe that explains the giant hat, like any movie Moricone scores has to have at least one cowboy hat. Hang tight, more late #inktober2023 on the way.

And here’s yesterday’s very late #Inktober, “CHAINS.” This guy is doing completely legitimate chainsaw stuff and observing some of the safety precautions, but not all of them. He should probably have full a face cover and over-ear hearing protection, but goggles and gloves are a start I guess. I’m not really an expert on actual chainsaw stuff, but last year I researched, wrote, hosted and produced a 17-minute long video feature on the history of chainsaws in video games. It was a lot of fun, but sadly hasn’t broken 35k views since then, which is not great. If you’d like to learn more about video game chainsaws, type “video game chainsaw history ign” into your favorite search engine and click on the video that’s 17 minutes long. Rated M for Mostly about chainsaw violence. #inktober2023

Still a day late! Here’s yesterday’s #inktober, “SCRATCHY.” Nobody or cat in particular inspired this, it just kind of came together as I was sketching and I think it’s funny, so here it is. Scratchy guy in a scratchy sweater being scratched by a cat. The carpet and office chair are probably also not very soft. What’s the scratchiest thing in your life? #inktober2023

Here’s yesterday’s #inktober, “CELESTIAL” which was an excuse to do one of the goofier Bloodborne bosses, the Celestial Emissary. That game starts out all werewolves and foul beasts and scary guys and then you start running into these goofy bastards, and you have to whip their dad’s ass in a courtyard for arcane cosmic reasons (and because he’s a jerk.) Anyway, Bloodborne rocks. #Inktober2023

Okay here’s yesterday’s #inktober “SHALLOW,” creepy crawly trigger warning for the second image. Here’s some context: when I was a kid, I lived along the not-that-deep Housatonic River. In the spring, you could flip over basically any rock along the banks and find a pile of Dobson fly larvae, otherwise known as HELLGRAMMITES - see photo, yes they’re usually that big. Neither of these kids is based on anyone in particular, but I did spend a day collecting these little nightmares in a paint roller tray (I can’t remember if we used kitchen tongs, probably not) and then selling them to fly-fishing tourist New Yorkers. I think we made seven or eight bucks, which kept us in Airheads and Skittles for a while. Hellgrammites have an extremely painful bite thanks to those big pincers, but luckily they’re not aggressive. Unless, ya know, you’re flipping over their rocks and trying to shove them into a paint roller tray. Photo credit to McFly Fishing Apparel. Paint roller tray credit to Dave Cadwell, I think. #inktober2023
October 25th’s #inktober word is “DANGEROUS,” so here’s a hogborg. That’s it. A cyborg hog. It’s not safe to be around, and is therefore… dangerous. #inktober2023

Here’s yesterday’s #inktober, “REMOVE.” I started it last night on very short plane ride home from a very short trip to LA, and it’s depicting a very short surgical procedure I had on Tuesday afternoon to get a cyst cut off the side of my head. It’s been a long week. Nothing serious, just a bunch of hair follicles decided to go rogue and turn into a gross little ball the size of a Milk Dud. Now I have stitches and a bunch of Vaseline in my hair. You probably needed to know all that about as much as I needed another hole in my head, but here we are. #inktober2023

Today’s #inktober is “BEAST,” so here’s that lovely first boss from Bloodborne, the Cleric Beast. This dude’s anatomy makes no sense, and he thrashes around so much it’s hard to get clear reference images, and in trying to actually finish today’s drawing prompt before it became yesterday’s, I almost bailed after scrapping my first sketch. But, much like how I played Bloodborne, I stubbornly brute forced my way to the finish line, relying not on skill so much as luck, guesswork, and spamming the cheapest techniques possible. I don’t think this is a good drawing, and I don’t think it’s a good painting, but I’m content with how it all came together, if that makes any sense. Anyway, may the good ink guide your way. #inktober2023

Yesterday was a whirlwind of frantic yard work, last-minute costume design, and finger food preparation followed by an abundance of social interaction at our Halloween party. So, I didn’t draw anything. BUT I did today. The #inktober word was “SPARKLE,” so here’s a guy having mixed feelings about how much the sparkling wine he does/doesn’t sparkle. #inktober2023

Here’s today’s #inktober, “MASSIVE.” I drew a massive reptile with a massive tummy ache from eating a massive bag of chips, which may or may not be rooted in some degree of self-portraiture. I definitely ate a bunch of very silly snacks in the last 48 hours. Maybe not a whole bag of Doritos, but comparable. #inktober2023

Right on schedule, here’s this year’s penultimate #inktober prompt, “RUSH.” This fella’s in a real hurry for work but luckily he’s double-fisting a tankshell of black coffee with an extra shot of espresso and a Red Bull Total Zero, and fun fact, friends: that much caffeine makes time slow down enough to be on time. But if you show up with two beverages, people will treat you like you’re late. Anyway I had today off work for unclear reasons so I actually did a bunch of fun lil’ doodles. Maybe I’ll post some more if you’re good. #inktober2023

And that’s a wrap on my first #inktober. The final prompt is “FIRE,”so here’s me sitting in my yard next to my fire pit, which does not have a fire in it because it always takes too long to burn down and it’s a school night so I’m going to bed early. It’s Halloween, so I’m dressed like an out of work lion tamer because I didn’t put on my whole costume and nobody really got it anyway (the woodsman from Over The Garden Wall, but it was too hot to wear the coat and carrying a bundle of firewood isn’t really practical indoors) and I was feeling kind of bummed because we never get trick or treaters, but as I was drawing this we got a few, which was nice. I’m glad I did this daily drawing thing, even if I was a day or two behind half the time. It’s kind of like exercise, in that it feels obnoxious and cultish to post about repeatedly on social media, but that adds a layer of motivation. Thanks to everyone who said nice supportive things about my little drawings, I’ll definitely make more! So long, #inktober2023 see you in hell. Or next year, whichever. Oh yeah also here’s the pens/tools I used all month. The clear things at the top are cheapo watercolor brush pens off Amazon and they’re not great. I have a Pentel one somewhere and it’s noticeably better quality.

Here’s this year’s family Halloween costume: Greg, Wirt and the old woodsman from Over The Garden Wall, a cartoon that more people need to watch (retroactively, so I don’t have to explain the costumes as much.) Full credit goes to @gennhaver for making the incredible tiny overalls, cape and hat completely from scratch. I spray painted the little teapot and sourced some bits and pieces online. Not pictured: elaborate bundle of sticks pruned from actual tree, painstakingly hand-trimmed to size, zip-tied together and then abandoned on the porch because screw it.
Oh yeah I made some gamer food, it tastes amazing but it makes your teeth hurt. It’s like a cross between Nerds Rope and a granola bar, but huge.

For my birthday this year, my awesome wife tracked down and connected me with the incredibly talented @cornkisser, whose particular tattooing style seemed like it’d lend itself to injecting some Dragon Ball art into my skin. If you’re not familiar, this is a pirate robot Goku and his pals run into in the very early pre-DBZ years. I’ve always loved the design, in no small part thanks to Akira Toriyama clearly taking inspiration from Giger’s Alien, so having a combination of two things I love reinterpreted by a local artist is something I’ll happily carry around with me until I’m dead or horribly dismembered. Special thanks to Best Day Ever Tattoo in Albany, CA for providing a wonderful atmosphere in which to get stabbed repeatedly for 5 hours straight.

I’m 37! After 30 it’s really only the decades that count, and 37 is so comically ungainly a number that it feels almost silly to celebrate it at all. However, that didn’t stop my incomparable wife @gennhaver from pulling out all the stops for an absolutely magnificent weekend. After wining, dining, and coordinating a tattoo for me, she got a bunch of my favorite people in one place, who then proceeded to shower me with affection and a literal embarrassment of thoughtful gifts. Setting clocks back and throwing out rotten jack-o-lanterns always makes this a dismal time of year, but this weekend’s festivities lifted my spirits, even if I had to take down the decorative Halloween ghosts. Thank you to everybody who said, did, or thought nice things about me this weekend (or any other, for that matter) I appreciate you. And yes, that’s a James Cameron’s Avatar gift bag, which @garfep somehow acquired in 2023.

Don’t quite have the same fire under my ass I did for inktober, but I’m still trying to knock out some art on a regular basis. In looking for inspiration, I pulled up a random word generator and shuffled it a few times until “BONUS” sparked a bit of inspiration.
Urine big trouble
AHHHHHHHHHH

I’m happy to report that I have the best sweater, which features Wolverine and Sabretooth kicking each others’ asses as they do on the covers of two issues from my favorite mid/late-80s run of X-Men comics. I own both the original comics it’s based on, unlike the 90s Jim Lee X-Men shirt that I’m wearing UNDER the sweater (not pictured) despite having that shirt in triplicate. Anyway, here’s me in my new sweater. Also, I’ve also been exercising a ton and I feel great about how I look but you’ll have to take my word for it because I’m wearing a large X-Men sweater. Nobody paid me for this post but the sweater is by @hufworldwide and I got it on sale at @pacsun.
My creep wife spies on me and the baby through the security system while I’m working and it’s shockingly flattering sometimes.
Hoping your January is more Januarish than Januariest and that the hounds of winter aren’t howling too loud
